        "newspaperPageNumber":"27",
        "trailText":"<strong>Letters:</strong> If Russell Brand campaigned for a fair voting system, perhaps people like me will applaud and not condemn",
        "headline":"Financial power, democratic corruption and lies",
        "body":"<p>It is good to see the IMF come round to the idea of a wealth tax as a way of resolving the current crisis. We suggested this three years ago in these pages (<a href=\"http://www.theguardian.com/commentisfree/2010/aug/15/deficit-crisis-tax-the-rich\" title=\"\">Let's be really in it together</a>, 16 August 2010), and the IMF has now made a similar calculation that a 10% levy could return European countries to pre-crisis public debt/GDP ratios (<a href=\"http://www.theguardian.com/business/economics-blog/2013/nov/05/moral-case-wealth-tax\" title=\"\">The moral case for a one-off wealth tax is compelling</a>, 5 November).</p><p>But the issue is not simply moral. The problem policymakers have still not faced is that the intense concentration of wealth at the top of society creates a mobility of private capital seeking rapid profitable investment. This is often in speculative activity, in commodities such as food, or as we are seeing once again in the frenzy gripping housing markets. Such capital needs to be recirculated into the economy in productive areas for social use but instead is destabilising in its effects, whether in the disaster of financial derivatives, or in producing the next housing crash.</p><p>The current bubble has of course been helped by the £130bn pumped in by the chancellor in an attempt to create the appearance of sustainable growth. It makes no economic sense, but politically it is attractive because over half the population live in homes which they own, and the house has become a touchstone of security where people are increasingly worried about pensions, employment, education fees and health. So a rise in house prices keeps the middle class temporarily happy, and partly explains why conservative politicians and the political system retain a legitimacy, however grudging.</p><p>Russell Brand is right to say that a large section of the population is excluded from this system (<a href=\"http://www.theguardian.com/commentisfree/2013/nov/05/russell-brand-democratic-system-newsnight\" title=\"\">A televised beginning to the Russell revolution</a>, 6 November). The bottom half of the population indeed have only 9% of the wealth. But the top half have the rest, and most will currently vote for either the existing coalition, or parties to the right of them. So a coherent alternative must be developed, in which social wealth is directed to social use, and it will have to be enacted through existing political structures, which have at least the formal power to direct taxation and economic policy. This means the hard, grinding work of electing committed politicians, of linking trade unions and activist groups, of bringing together the excluded, and fighting for the true representation of political alternatives in a media so dominated by the constant assumption that \"there is no alternative\".<br /><strong>Professor Greg Philo</strong><br /><em>Glasgow University Media Group</em></p><p></p><p>• David Runciman's discussion of democracy (<a href=\"http://www.theguardian.com/books/2013/nov/08/trouble-with-democracy-david-runciman\" title=\"\">Dictator envy?</a>, Review, 9 November) was interesting and perceptive, but he was not perceptive enough to notice the herd of elephants charging through his study as he wrote. The elephants presently trampling democracy under their huge feet are international companies.</p><p>The power of international capitalism, with some companies having greater wealth than many nations, is in the process of destroying democracy. Companies are deciding for themselves whether and where they pay taxes, and using the threat of closing factories to control wages and humiliate unions. Democratic governments have to bribe them with grants and special freedoms so that they will kindly make money in their countries. Democracies that cannot control their economies are in real trouble.</p><p>The power of international capitalism is the main cause of the diseases of recent politics, including a disengaged electorate. It has forced all major parties, of right and left, to converge on the \"centre\" ground, which can be interpreted as an acceptance of a neoliberal market economy. Genuine choice has been removed. The only answer seems to be merging small nations into large conglomerates such as the EU – with the subsequent loss of any real feeling of involvement in democracy. I only hope that David Runciman is right and democracy will muddle through in the end.<br /><strong>Professor Trevor Hussey</strong><br /><em>High Wycombe, Buckinghamshire</em></p><p></p><p>• In the early 70s I campaigned against homelessness (\"land for people, not for profit\"), helping homeless people get out of \"halfway houses\" and into needlessly empty property, thus preventing \"prior demolition\" (homes being demolished before a public inquiry). I researched and co-compiled Shelter's Bed &amp; Breakfast Report (1974) and had posters in my window: \"Don't Vote – It Only Encourages Them\" and \"Whoever You Vote For, the Government Gets In\".</p><p>Then, I was encouraged to join the Labour party by a prominent politician and, apart from several years' lapse as a protest against the Iraq war, I have remained for 40 years. But, with 80,000 children currently in B&amp;B accommodation, I believe Russell Brand has a point. It's up to politicians to prove him wrong.<br /><strong>Mary Evans Young</strong><br /><em>Banbury, Oxfordshire</em></p><p></p><p>• If Jeremy Paxman thinks the tuition fees U-turn is one of the most blatant lies of recent political history (<a href=\"http://www.theguardian.com/politics/2013/nov/07/russell-brand-row-nick-clegg-jeremy-paxman\" title=\"\">Clegg says Paxman makes good living sneering at politics</a>, 8 November), one rather wonders where he's been during the last decade. I think the lies told around Iraq must beat almost anything we have been misled on by recent administrations.</p><p>As to serious defects in our political processes (<a href=\"http://www.theguardian.com/culture/2013/nov/06/russell-brand-ideas-great-where-strategy\" title=\"\">Letters</a>, 7 November) surely the first-past-the-post electoral system must take the honours. Nick Clegg tried and failed to begin to right this wrong, albeit with a system of proportional representation which was not the best but at least a step in the right direction.Because the popular press hated Nick Clegg more than they valued a fair voting system, the referendum buried the attempt. I fear another attempt will not happen in my lifetime.</p><p>If only Russell Brand would halt his blathering and come up with something useful in order to challenge the status quo and inspire the non-voters instead of washing his hands in public of his responsibility to his fellow citizens.</p><p>Campaign, Mr Brand, for a fair voting system. Then perhaps people like me will applaud and not condemn. As for Paxman, perhaps he should call it a day since he feels so cynical about those he uses and abuses to make his living. <br /><strong>Ann Smith</strong><br /><em>Stockport</em></p><p></p><p>• Nick Clegg is quite wrong to criticise Jeremy Paxman for \"sneering about politics\". Paxman is not sneering about politics, but about politicians. Only someone who has a belief that our political system should deliver better would be driven to criticise the daily tide of spin, shattered promises, operational incompetence and self-preservation in which we voters are drenched by the Rt Hon Nick Clegg's generation of fellow career MPs.<br /><strong>Simon Cherry</strong><br /><em>Claygate, Surrey</em></p><!-- Guardian Watermark: internal-code/content/422127451|2013-11-11T15:34:09Z|deccd11dafe73175fef42138a51b4fb6751199bb -->",
