      "id":"commentisfree/2013/nov/06/russell-brand-democracy-radical-hero",
      "sectionId":"commentisfree",
      "sectionName":"Comment is free",
      "webPublicationDate":"2013-11-06T11:30:37Z",
      "webTitle":"Russell Brand: mad, bad and dangerous for democracy? | Anne Perkins",
      "webUrl":"http://www.theguardian.com/commentisfree/2013/nov/06/russell-brand-democracy-radical-hero",
      "apiUrl":"http://content.guardianapis.com/commentisfree/2013/nov/06/russell-brand-democracy-radical-hero",
      "fields":{
        "trailText":"<strong>Anne Perkins: First thoughts: </strong>Here he is, a radical hero for our times. But democratic renewal requires not heroes but an educated, demanding electorate",
        "headline":"Russell Brand: mad, bad and dangerous for democracy?",
        "body":"<p>The last time there was an economic meltdown on the scale of the one from which Europe may now be slowly and painfully emerging, it destroyed democracy and ended in war. This time – despite nasty outbreaks of neo-fascism even in unlikely quarters like the Netherlands – it's brought us Russell Brand, political hero. If he knew a bit more history, he might be a bit more careful about who and what he attacks.</p><p>Perhaps he should start with The Pike, Lucy Hughes-Hallett's new biography of <a href=\"http://www.theguardian.com/books/2013/nov/06/lucy-hughes-hallett-prize-biography-interview\" title=\"\">Gabriele D'Annunzio</a>, which has just won the Samuel Johnson non-fiction prize. There's something about the romanticism that imbues <a href=\"http://www.theguardian.com/commentisfree/2013/nov/05/russell-brand-democratic-system-newsnight\" title=\"\">Brand's description of the state of democracy</a> that feels a little like the distorted utopianism of the Italian proto-fascist, for whom Byron (the Russell Brand of his day) was an early hero.</p><p>The core Brand message, which is \"I am naive, and I have screwed up, but I tell you something, I believe in change\", is perfectly pitched (Byron: \"Pleasure's a sin and sometimes sin's a pleasure\"). Here he is, a hero for our times, idealist, hedonist, radical. Above all, individual, yet also a man of the crowd, <a href=\"http://www.theguardian.com/world/2013/nov/06/protesters-gather-million-mask-march\" title=\"\">out with the Million Mask protesters last night</a>, demanding something different, a world where everyone loves everyone else and we'll all agree with Russell because what to do if we don't isn't in the manifesto.</p><p>Brand's voice resonates around cyberspace. There is a great hunger for change and a dangerous sense of powerlessness. The world is longing for a hero who can see how to put things right. It's just that heroes are really bad for democracy. For democracy, boringly, depends on bringing people with you, step by step, not just spotting where they'd like to be in their dreams and declaring that you can take them there.</p><p>That's why democracy needs political parties. The trouble is they can be bad for democracy too. The search for a majority ends up with bland politics and bland politicians. Fertile territory for the hero. Even so, the Brand appeal is harder to pull off when you are actually in power, though that's not stopping <a href=\"http://www.theguardian.com/commentisfree/2013/nov/05/toronto-mayor-resign-rob-ford-crack-allegations\" title=\"\">Rob Ford, the drink-and-drug-stricken mayor of Toronto</a>. Last night, with a catch in his voice, he begged voters to let him go on being mayor despite his tendency to ricochet unsteadily off studio cameras during live TV appearances. Astonishingly, it seems just possible that being authentic, as such openness is described these days, may be just what's needed to distract voters from rather more serious charges as painstakingly uncovered by the city's leading newspaper, the Toronto Star.</p><p>The trouble poor old democracy has is that it depends on a romantic idea, when it only works if it's an unglamorous grind. \"Campaign in poetry, govern in prose,\" as Aneurin Bevan, probably the last politician capable of heroic oratory along with quite high grade administrative skills, used to say. Politicians have to sell the romance and then put in the graft, and the tragedy of experience is that romance loses its appeal. Poor old Ed Miliband, balancing the ambitions of his party, the unions and the country, he cannot hope to compete with the Russell Brand party of Russell Brand.</p><p>But party Brand couldn't change anything without becoming the Napoleon of the revolution. What democracy needs to work is an educated, demanding electorate, President Eisenhower's alert and knowledgeable citizenry. (He also had a good line about bad officials being elected by good voters who didn't vote). Demagoguery is not entirely dangerous. Its purpose is to remind us why the boring bits of democracy actually matter.</p><!-- Guardian Watermark: internal-code/content/421789054|2013-11-11T15:34:09Z|cb6ef7ee8b44aa0c4c937d1cbb7893d57259da3f -->",
