      "id":"commentisfree/2013/nov/08/jeremy-paxman-nick-clegg-parasite-ignorance",
      "sectionId":"commentisfree",
      "sectionName":"Comment is free",
      "webPublicationDate":"2013-11-08T18:59:15Z",
      "webTitle":"Jeremy Paxman is as much 'stuck in' politics as you or I, Nick Clegg | Marina Hyde",
      "webUrl":"http://www.theguardian.com/commentisfree/2013/nov/08/jeremy-paxman-nick-clegg-parasite-ignorance",
      "apiUrl":"http://content.guardianapis.com/commentisfree/2013/nov/08/jeremy-paxman-nick-clegg-parasite-ignorance",
      "fields":{
        "newspaperPageNumber":"54",
        "trailText":"<strong>Marina Hyde:</strong> To cast the Newsnight presenter as a parasite reveals Clegg's alarming delusion that politics is only done by politicians",
        "headline":"Jeremy Paxman is as much 'stuck in' politics as you or I, Nick Clegg",
        "body":"<p>Ever the pessimist, I never dreamed anyone could top <a href=\"http://www.theguardian.com/commentisfree/2013/sep/08/despise-politicians-my-part-murdoch-machine\" title=\"\">Chris Huhne's confusion</a> as to why a newspaper should have reported on his crime and misdemeanours. But&nbsp;what an enchantment to be proved wrong, and by none other than Chris's erstwhile leader <a href=\"http://www.theguardian.com/politics/2013/nov/07/russell-brand-row-nick-clegg-jeremy-paxman\" title=\"\">Nick Clegg, who this week offered his own view</a> of the iniquities of politicians being held to&nbsp;account.</p><p>\"Here is a guy …\" he opined of Jeremy Paxman to listeners to his LBC phone-in, \"he lives off politics and he spends all his time sneering at politics.\" Eh? It's always alarming to hear a politician say what they actually think – though given that <a href=\"http://www.theguardian.com/politics/shortcuts/2013/nov/06/nick-clegg-fan-spin-emma-gilpin-jacobs\" title=\"\">Clegg's office staff has risen to 20</a> – 20! – you'd think there could these days be a minimum of three handlers on site in any situation in which he might make an unscripted utterance. But this revelation is more alarming than most, with the deputy prime minister apparently casting someone who holds politicians to account as a sort of parasite.</p><p>As someone who has only spent his entire professional life in politics, this may come as a shock to Clegg, but Paxman does not live off politics, any more than voters or protesters or pressure groups do. Politics is an ecosystem, of which Westminster is a component. But this ecosystem includes all manner of components other than Clegg's green-bench colleagues, from voters to non-voters to rioters to journalists to protesters to vested interests and all sorts of others besides. It should be blindingly obvious, even to a Brussels-product such as Clegg, that it includes those who ask difficult or disparaging questions of politicians – and even those who dismiss them altogether.</p><p>Without wishing to overload Clegg with further enlightenment, Westminster MPs do not \"own\" politics, any more than the Christian church owns marriage, which was knocking around as an idea long before Jesus was even a glint in the Holy Spirit's eye. They are simply part of it.</p><p>Indeed, if holding people to account were left solely to those whom Clegg would class as politicians, we'd all be the poorer. The dramatic rise in profile of the committee system in recent times has too often laid bare the disappointing calibre of MP inquisitors, with the <a href=\"http://www.theguardian.com/world/2013/nov/07/nsa-leaks-enemies-rubbing-hands-glee-mi6\" title=\"\">spy chiefs' appearance before the intelligence and security committee</a> this week being a case in point. \"Sir John, do you want to say anything?\" wondered Malcolm Rifkind of the head of MI6, deploying the sort of hardball inquiry This Morning's Holly Willoughby might lob at someone who'd just been voted off Strictly Come Dancing. If only it had been possible to bring on John Humphrys – or indeed an appalled member of the surveilled public – who might have felt less instinctively deferential.</p><p>Whatever people say about the US, it at least embraces the filth and fury of politics, and puts the whole malfunctioning and fetid business out there for all to see. In Nick Clegg's unwittingly revelatory aside on those who \"live off\" politics, there is some of the rarefied disdain of the EU, where he was politically schooled, where it is regarded as vulgar to make too many inquiries as to what the overlords are up to, and where public adversarialism is shunned in favour of private machinations. In his reflexive sense that politics should somehow be beyond the irreverent attentions of what Tony Blair called \"the sneerers\" lies the germ of what so many people loathe about Brussels.</p><p>Unhappily, though, the deputy prime minister was not done. \"At the end of the day,\" Clegg expanded to LBC listeners, \"I have got this old-fashioned view that if you want to change something, get stuck in and get your hands dirty.\"</p><p>Of all the idiotic arguments about criticism, deployed almost without exception by those who can't take it, there is none more extravagantly stupid than one that says you can't criticise something unless you've actually done it yourself. By this logic, neither you nor I should have the temerity to offer an opinion about some $200m Hollywood turkey unless we have personally had a crack at the form.</p><p>A little tip for Nick: most people in the country, whether they vote or not, \"get stuck in\" to politics every day of their lives, whether they care to or not. We live politics, to varying degrees, with the sad irony that those who might feel most voiceless in politics are the ones with the most politics in their lives, usually via the welfare state. If Clegg really wants an example of that rare group, those who have the luxury of not having to get stuck into politics, we might offer him the bankers, who have been given such a free run by the self-styled custodians of politics in Westminster that they now exist in a sort of post-politics wonderland, where socialism is evil unless it is required to bail out capitalism, and other looking-glass inversions.</p><p>The rest of us are still very much stuck into politics, and indeed to economics, and just because we haven't taken the decision to become a career politician and devote our lives to the noble business of trooping where we're told in the voting lobbies, or attempting to get the taxpayer to fund our patio furniture, doesn't mean we have forfeited the right to an opinion. I'm no electoral strategist, but I wonder whether \"keep politics for the politicians\" is quite the 2015 slogan the Lib Dems want to be going for.</p><p><em>Twitter: </em><a href=\"https://twitter.com/MarinaHyde\" title=\"\"><em>@MarinaHyde</em></a></p><!-- Guardian Watermark: internal-code/content/422031607|2013-11-11T15:34:09Z|87b0d54ebb5d573f663981fdab2285af4189d283 -->",
